ession","Retina","Brain tissue","Pituitary gland","Nasal septum"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emuscles of facial expression\u003C/strong\u003E are supplied by branches of the external carotid artery, specifically via the facial and superficial temporal arteries. The external carotid artery supplies structures external to the cranium including the face, scalp, and neck.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetina\u003C/strong\u003E is supplied by the ophthalmic artery, a branch of the internal carotid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrain tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is supplied by the anterior and middle cerebral arteries, branches of the internal carotid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPituitary gland\u003C/strong\u003E is supplied by the superior and inferior hypophyseal arteries from the internal carotid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasal septum\u003C/strong\u003E receives a dual blood supply - anteriorly from the sphenopalatine artery (internal carotid) and the superior labial branch of the facial artery (external carotid), and posteriorly from branches of the internal carotid (however supply is not \u003Cem\u003Eprimarily \u003C/em\u003Efrom this vessel)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the distribution of the external versus internal carotid arteries is clinically important when considering the blood supply of head and neck structures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The external carotid artery supplies structures external to the skull including the face, scalp, and neck.","The internal carotid artery supplies intracranial structures and the orbit.","The common carotid artery bifurcates at the level 